author: NEW YORK DAILY NEWS
title: Thousands line up for Columbus Day parade in NYC
text:
Go Nakamura/For New York Daily News Members of Frank Sinatra School of Arts sing Sinatra's hit songs on the New York Daily News float for Columbus Day Parade NYC on October 12, 2015 in Manhattan. Seth Wenig/AP New York Governor Andrew Cuomo, second from left, poses for a picture with members of the Harlem Globetrotters before marching in the Columbus Day Parade in New York, Monday, Oct. 12, 2015. Approximately 35,000 marchers participated in the annual celebration of Italian-American culture. (AP Photo/Seth Wenig) Go Nakamura/For New York Daily News Performers dance at the annual Columbus Day Parade NYC on October 12, 2015 in Manhattan. Andrew Burton/Getty Images A girl rides on a float with a bust of Christopher Columbus' head during the Columbus Day Parade on Fifth Avenue on October 12, 2015 in New York City. Andrew Burton/Getty Images Dancers participate in the Columbus Day Parade on Fifth Avenue on October 12, 2015 in New York City. Previous Next Enlarge Thousands of people have lined New York's Fifth Avenue to cheer the annual Columbus Day parade in the nation's largest city.
Marching bands, floats and politicians marched up the famous thoroughfare Monday.
Beyond commemorating Columbus, the parade has also become a celebration of New Yorkers of Italian heritage.
Go Nakamura/For New York Daily News Mayor Bill de Blasio participated Columbus Day Parade NY and marched up on 5th Ave on Monday October 12, 2015 in Manhattan.
New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo and Mayor Bill de Blasio are each of Italian descent. They were warmly received along the route.
But the two men have been locked in a bitter political feud and did not interact during the festivities.
The crowds were enthusiastic on a mild fall day, but the parade also annually elicits criticism.
Some people gathered near the parade to celebrate what they called Indigenous People Day out of protest of Christopher Columbus' treatment of Native Americans.
